August 13, 1942
For Albert &amp; Hilda,
(Remembering their garden wedding.)
<lg><l>Whatever skies may darken</l>
<l>One blue-gold noon remains</l>
<l>Forever, hushed to harken</l>
<l>Between the April rains; </l>
<l>Serene in living <strike/> glory</l>
<l>With what it hears &amp; heard -</l>
<l>The new-old sacred story,</l></lg>
<strike/>
<strike/>
<lg><l>And one applauding bird.</l>
<l>The hedges still are leaning,</l>
<l>The fountain's tinkle dies</l>
<l>To hear the hush, and meaning</l>
<l>Of what  it prophecies;</l>
<l>And two made one shall hear it</l>
<l>As long aas life endures:</l>
<l><underline>The good red road of spirit,</l>
<l>The hard black road are yours.</underline></l></lg>
<strike>But</strike>
<strike/>
<lg><underline><l>But holy, failing never,</l>
<l>Their crossing place shall be</l>
<l>For there shall spring forever</l>
<l>And soar the shieldign tree</l></underline></lg>
21
<lg><l>And when two hearts thereunder</l>
<l>Recall the plighted words,</l>
<l>The tree shall bloom with wonder</l>
<l>And fill with singing birds</l></lg>
(Aug. 13, '42)
J.G.N.